00:01:24.230 --> 00:01:28.290
It hit at a low angle with the force of at least a 100 kiloton nuclear

00:01:28.310 --> 00:01:32.470
bomb. Yet much of the debris fell back onto the asteroid.

00:01:32.490 --> 00:01:36.500
The particles that escaped were the smallest ones. Easily

00:01:36.520 --> 00:01:40.570
pushed around by sunlight, this fine dust formed wispy plumes.

00:01:40.590 --> 00:01:44.590
When Hubble observed Scheila two weeks later, the

00:01:44.610 --> 00:01:48.620
plumes were barely visible. Within two months of the outburst,

00:01:48.640 --> 00:01:52.690
the plumes were completely gone--and with them went any sign from Earth that Scheila even had

00:01:52.710 --> 00:01:56.710
a collision. Astronomers estimate that, somewhere in the asteroid

00:01:56.730 --> 00:02:00.750
belt, events like this may happen as often as every year. Thanks to Hubble and

00:02:00.770 --> 00:02:04.860
Swift, we're just beginning to see them.

